Reni Kaul

We’ve created data visualization using many of the default settings. Today we will spend time exploring different visualizations using the ggplot2 package. Focus on creating a visualization for presentation.

At a minimum figures should have:

  • labeled axes with units
  • legend with meaningful labels

Challenge 1

Today we will explore the weather dataset that is part of the nycflights13 data package. The weather dataset consists of hourly meterological data for LGA, JFK and EWR airports for all of 2013. If we were interested in the annual trend in tempature we could make a box plot of the recorded temperatures for each month.

Using base R, the code and plot look like this:

library(nycflights13) #load data from package

boxplot(weather$temp ~ weather$month, xlab="month", ylab="Temperature (F)" ) #instead of assigning x and y values, you can use the syntax y ~ x

Today, your challenge is to recreate this figure using the ggplot2 package. ggplot2 was first published to CRAN in 2005, so a quick google search will return MANY tutorials, discussion pages, etc. The general syntax for boxplots in ggplot2 is:

ggplot(data, #matrix
       aes(x= X.col, y= Y.col)) + #x and y columns in matrix to plot
      geom_boxplot() #plot the data as a box plot

A basic ggplot2 boxplot should look like this:

With additional customization, we can produce a plot with a little more shine. For example, this plot has transparent colored boxes and month names instead of numbers.

Work with your team to create a polished ggplot2 boxplot. It doesn’t need to look like these figures, but you are welcome to use them as a guide. If you need guidance, check out the ggplot2 cheat sheet. A very detailed tutorial is on ZevRoss. A more formal guide is in the R for Data Science visualization chapter.

Challenge 2

For this exercise, we will use diamonds in the ggplot2 package. The ggplot2 package should already be loaded. Explore the diamonds dataset which contains 10 attributes (price, cut, clarity, etc.) for ~54,000 diamonds.

So far we have only created single panel visualizations. Making multipanel visualizations is a quick way to look at trends between covariates. Here the x-axis is diamond carat, y-axis price, and each panel is diamond cut.

Your goal is to create this figure, and modify it in at least 2 ways. The syntax for a multipanel or facet plot is similar to a scatterplot but uses facet_wrap() in addition to geom_point().
